VThere is a huge difference between someone saying "I think this film is really good, you should watch it" and "I think this film is really good, you should watch it, by the way I am being paid to say this". The difference is as big as the difference between someone who has sex with you for money and someone who has sex with you because they want to have sex with you. The difference is big enough that we should use different words to describe the act of saying them - we should use the word "recommendation" for one, and another word for the other.\u000a\u000aThe word "advertizing" is the label I think we might as well give to the second person. Going by my definition, most examples of what people would USUALLY call advertizing (billboards, TV ads, radio ads) will be labelled correctly.\u000a\u000aAdmittedly, there are some things like movie trailers that most people will call adverts but which will not be adverts by my definition.\u000a\u000a[[Hang on, you think that movie trailers are NOT adverts? |Movie trailers]] \u000a[[Alright, so what's bad about that?|Start]]\u000a[[That's still not a definition of advertizing that should be used|Apologism for the definition]] \u000a
