V"Slippery slopes", in general, are not as much of a problem as they are made out to be. For example, some people see legalizing gay marriage as a slippery slope toward legalizing beastiality and incest, because it opens up the word "marriage" to reinterpretation. But this is not a very plausible prediction.\u000a\u000aAdvertizing has actually already been banned in many places. Sao Paolo and other cities have banned billboards, Spain made "Cult of the body" adverts illegal, and in Sweden advertizing to children has been illegal since 1991. Product placement, which is mostly indistinguishable from advertizing, used to be illegal in the UK. But these countries have not been caused to slide down a slope towards crushing illiberalism, so far as I am aware.\u000a\u000a[[I do not accept this. |Give up]]\u000a[[Fine, but why take the risk by banning advertizing at all?|Arguments against advertizing 1]]\u000a
